<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="176" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,153,1440]" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,981,1007]" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">Host plants</emphasis>
. The adults have been collected on the dead alder and birch (
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. Hara" authorityYear="1937" baseAuthorityName="Miq." box="[1011,1368,981,1007]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="platyphylla" variety="japonica">
<emphasis box="[1011,1216,981,1007]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">Betula platyphylla</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[1270,1368,982,1007]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) trees (
<bibRefCitation author="Takeuchi, K." box="[158,329,1017,1043]" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" pagination="173 - 229" refId="ref6948" refString="Takeuchi, K. (1938) A systematic study on the suborder Symphyta (Hymenoptera) of the Japanese Empire (1). Tenthredo, 2, 173 - 229." type="journal article" year="1938">Takeuchi 1938</bibRefCitation>
; see Appendix), which may prove to be the host plant. A series of specimens from Mt. Irumukeppu were obtained by “branch trapping” but the host tree was not noted on the labels. It is interesting that we examined several specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Takeuchi" authorityYear="1938" box="[400,525,1089,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Xiphydriidae" genus="Xiphydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="camelus">
<emphasis box="[400,525,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">X. camelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the same data (see Appendix). 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Takeuchi" authorityYear="1938" box="[951,1165,1089,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Xiphydriidae" genus="Xiphydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="camelus">
<emphasis box="[951,1165,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">Xiphydria camelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shinohara &amp; Kameda" authorityYear="2019" box="[1225,1365,1089,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Xiphydriidae" genus="Xiphydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albopicta">
<emphasis box="[1225,1365,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">X. albopicta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occur together and possibly feed on the same host species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="176" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,153,1440]" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1161,1187]" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">Remarks</emphasis>
. The present new species is generally similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Takeuchi" authorityYear="1938" box="[848,971,1161,1187]" class="Insecta" family="Xiphydriidae" genus="Xiphydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="camelus">
<emphasis box="[848,971,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">X. camelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Konow" authorityYear="1899" box="[1024,1142,1161,1187]" class="Insecta" family="Xiphydriidae" genus="Xiphydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eborata">
<emphasis box="[1024,1142,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">X. eborata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but can be separated from them by the combination of the almost entirely pale reddish brown legs and presence of a large creamy white mark covering the lower inner orbit through the malar space and the lower part of gena. The clypeus and supraclypeal area are usually mostly or entirely black (
<figureCitation box="[564,651,1269,1295]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1766,1791]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,477,1754]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,477,1754]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Xiphydria camelus (A, B), X. albopicta (C–E) and X. eborata (F–I), heads in dorsofrontal view, females.—A, Hikawa-rindo, Honshu, Japan; B, Kangaslampi, Finland; C, holotype; D, Fuuren, Hokkaido, Japan; E, Ashibetsu, Hokkaido, Japan; F, Sounkyo, Hokkaido, Japan; G, syntype of X. eborata; H, lectotype of X. kawakamii; I, lectotype of X. kuccharonis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3404825/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
), but sometimes partly or almost entirely pale brown or creamy white (
<figureCitation box="[160,282,1305,1331]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1766,1791]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,477,1754]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,477,1754]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Xiphydria camelus (A, B), X. albopicta (C–E) and X. eborata (F–I), heads in dorsofrontal view, females.—A, Hikawa-rindo, Honshu, Japan; B, Kangaslampi, Finland; C, holotype; D, Fuuren, Hokkaido, Japan; E, Ashibetsu, Hokkaido, Japan; F, Sounkyo, Hokkaido, Japan; G, syntype of X. eborata; H, lectotype of X. kawakamii; I, lectotype of X. kuccharonis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3404825/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">Fig. 3D, E</figureCitation>
). The elongate creamy white spot on the lateral posterior part of gena is often connected to the spot on the lower part of gena, almost always so in the males (
<figureCitation box="[760,851,1341,1367]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1939,1964]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,250,1927]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,261,1927]" captionText="FIGURE 4. Xiphydria camelus (A, F), X. albopicta (B, G) and X. eborata (C–E, H), females (A–D) and males (E–H).—A, Kangaslampi, Finland; B, holotype; C, syntype of X. eborata; D, Sounkyo, Hokkaido, Japan; E, H, lectotype of X. jozana; F, Satsunaigawa, Hokkaido, Japan; G, Pirikaneppu, Hokkaido, Japan." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3404827/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">Fig. 4G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,153,1440]" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">
A series of specimens from Teshio examined are part of the material of 
<emphasis box="[1009,1203,1377,1403]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">
<taxonomicName authority="Shinohara &amp; Kameda, 2019" authorityName="Shinohara &amp; Kameda" authorityYear="2019" box="[1009,1133,1377,1403]" class="Insecta" family="Xiphydriidae" genus="Xiphydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="camelus" status="s. lat.">X. camelus</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1140,1203,1377,1403]" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" sensu="lato">s. lat.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
studied by 
<bibRefCitation author="Takeuchi, K." pageId="5" pageNumber="176" pagination="173 - 229" refId="ref6948" refString="Takeuchi, K. (1938) A systematic study on the suborder Symphyta (Hymenoptera) of the Japanese Empire (1). Tenthredo, 2, 173 - 229." type="journal article" year="1938">Takeuchi (1938)</bibRefCitation>
, who called them the form 1 (light form).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
